    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-03-25T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-03-25T10:00:00-05:00" n="908"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d908">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/9322: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ankara</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-03-25T18:00:00+03:00"
                            >March 25, 1941—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 10:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>80. For Secretary and Under Secretary. I now learn that at Cyprus conference
                    reported in my 74, March 21, Turks agreed to make fresh overtures to Yugoslavs
                    for conference as to possible joint action in event of attack upon Saloniki
                    which, if latter agreed, Turks would be prepared to regard a “mortal danger”
                    (rather than “casus belli” as attitude reported in my 39, February 24<note
                        n="41" xml:id="d908fn41">Not printed.</note> would have warranted
                    expecting); but that in view of Yugoslav crisis reported in Belgrade’s 219,
                    March 21,<note n="42" xml:id="d908fn42">
                        <ref target="frus1941v02#pg_963">Vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p.
                            963</ref>.</note> Turkish Government suspended action on that
                    undertaking and has only now consented under British pressure to send its
                    Ambassador seemingly futile instructions to act thereon if he finds occasion
                    suitable.</p>
                <p>Repeated Athens, Belgrade.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
